Preheat your oven to 220 degrees. Pop the @corn tortillas{2} in a single layer on a
large lightly oiled #baking tray{} and drizzle over some @oil{}. Sprinkle over some
@salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Keep to one side.

Cut the @echalion shallot{1} in half through the root. Peel and then thinly slice
into half moon shapes. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic
press{} if you have one). Remove the core from the @yellow pepper{1}, then thinly
slice into 1cm wide strips. Cut the top and bottom off the @courgette{1}, then cut
in half lengthways, cut each half into four long lengths and then chop into roughly
1cm chunks. Drain the @mixed beans{1} in a #colander{} and rinse under cold
running water.

Put a #frying pan{} on medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. Add your shallot,
pepper and courgette along with a pinch of @salt{} and a grind of @black pepper{}.
Cook for ~{5-6%minutes} until slightly browned.

Add your garlic and @Mexican spice{1.5} (add less spice if you're not a fan of heat!)
to your mixture. Stir together and cook for ~{1%minute} more until fragrant, then
add the @tinned plum tomatoes{1}. Add the @vegetable stock pot{1/2}. Stir until
it dissolves then add your mixed beans. Stir together and cook for
~{10-15%minutes} until the liquid has reduced by half.

> If your mixture looks too dry, just add 1 tbsp of water!

Meanwhile, pop your tortillas on the top shelf of your #oven{} for ~{6-10%minutes}.
Keep an eye on them, you want them to be golden and crispy but not burnt! Once
cooked, remove from your oven and lay on some #kitchen paper{} to absorb any excess
oil.

Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30}(g). Slice lengthways into the @avocado{1},
once you reach the stone turn your avocado around to cut it in half. Twist each
half and pull it apart. Remove the stone then scoop out all the insides into a
#bowl{}. Roughly chop the @coriander{1} (both stalks and leaves, but keep separate)
and add your stalks and half your leaves to your avocado. Squeeze in a good splash
of @lime{1/2} juice and mash together with a #fork{}. You've just made guacamole!

> It should still be a little lumpy for that rustic look!

Assemble your tostadas by laying one on each #plate{}, piling high with your veggie
beans, then adding some cheese and a dollop of guacamole. Finish with a sprinkle of
your remaining coriander leaves and tuck in!